Below is a **clean, real‑world, production‑ready way to combine JWT with Redux roles**, exactly how it’s done in enterprise React apps.

I’ll show **architecture + flow + code**, and also explain **what NOT to do** (very important).

***

# ✅ Goal

✅ Use **JWT** as the **source of truth** for user identity & roles  
✅ Store **roles in Redux** (for UI behavior only)  
✅ Protect **routes, components, and Redux selectors**  
✅ Keep **security on the backend**, UX control on frontend

***

# 🧠 Core Principle (MEMORIZE)

> **JWT = Authentication & Authorization source**  
> **Redux = UI‑level state & role‑based rendering**

🚫 Redux is **NOT** security  
✅ Backend must still validate JWT on every request

***

# ✅ High‑Level Architecture

    Backend
     └─ Issues JWT (userId + roles)

    React App
     ├─ Reads JWT (login / refresh)
     ├─ Decodes roles
     ├─ Stores roles in Redux
     ├─ Uses roles for:
     │    - Route protection
     │    - Component rendering
     │    - Role‑guarded selectors

***

# ✅ Step 1: JWT Payload (BACKEND)

Your backend must include roles **inside the JWT**

### ✅ Example JWT payload

```json
{
  "sub": "12345",
  "name": "Raja",
  "roles": ["ADMIN", "USER"],
  "exp": 1713571200
}
```

✅ JWT is **signed**  
✅ Frontend **cannot modify it**

***

# ✅ Step 2: Login → Decode JWT → Store Roles in Redux

## 🔐 Login API Response

```json
{
  "accessToken": "eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9..."
}
```

***

## ✅ Decode JWT (Frontend)

Use a decoder library:

```bash
npm install jwt-decode
```

```js
import jwtDecode from "jwt-decode";

const decoded = jwtDecode(accessToken);
/*
decoded = {
  sub: "12345",
  name: "Raja",
  roles: ["ADMIN"]
}
*/
```

✅ **Decoding ≠ verification**  
✅ Verification happens on backend

***

# ✅ Step 3: Redux Auth Slice (Roles stored here)

```js
// store/slices/authSlice.js
const initialState = {
  isAuthenticated: false,
  user: null,
  roles: []
};

const authSlice = createSlice({
  name: "auth",
  initialState,
  reducers: {
    loginSuccess(state, action) {
      const { user, roles } = action.payload;
      state.isAuthenticated = true;
      state.user = user;
      state.roles = roles;
    },
    logout(state) {
      state.isAuthenticated = false;
      state.user = null;
      state.roles = [];
    }
  }
});

export const { loginSuccess, logout } = authSlice.actions;
export default authSlice.reducer;
```

✅ Redux stores **roles only**  
❌ Redux does NOT store JWT access tokens long‑term

***

# ✅ Step 4: Dispatch Roles After Login

```js
const decoded = jwtDecode(accessToken);

dispatch(loginSuccess({
  user: {
    id: decoded.sub,
    name: decoded.name
  },
  roles: decoded.roles
}));
```

✅ Single source of UI truth  
✅ Easy to reset on logout

***

# ✅ Step 5: Role Selectors (Public API)

```js
// store/selectors/authSelectors.js
export const selectRoles = state => state.auth.roles;

export const hasRole = role => state =>
  state.auth.roles.includes(role);
```

***

# ✅ Step 6: Role‑Guarded Hooks (BEST PRACTICE)

```js
// store/hooks/useAdminAccess.js
import { useSelector } from "react-redux";

export function useAdminAccess() {
  const roles = useSelector(state => state.auth.roles);

  if (!roles.includes("ADMIN")) {
    throw new Error("ADMIN access required");
  }

  return true;
}
```

### ✅ Usage

```jsx
function AdminPanel() {
  useAdminAccess();
  return <div>Admin Area ✅</div>;
}
```

✅ Prevents accidental misuse  
✅ Self‑documenting  
✅ Scales well

***

# ✅ Step 7: Route Protection with Roles

```jsx
function RequireRole({ role, children }) {
  const roles = useSelector(selectRoles);
  return roles.includes(role)
    ? children
    : <Navigate to="/403" />;
}
```

```jsx
<Route
  path="/admin"
  element={
    <RequireRole role="ADMIN">
      <AdminPanel />
    </RequireRole>
  }
/>
```

***

# ✅ Step 8: Redux + JWT + API Calls (IMPORTANT)

JWT is sent with requests:

```js
fetch("/api/admin", {
  headers: {
    Authorization: `Bearer ${accessToken}`
  }
});
```

✅ Backend verifies JWT  
✅ Backend checks roles again  
✅ Redux just controls UI

***

# 🚫 WHAT NOT TO DO (CRITICAL)

### ❌ Do NOT trust Redux for security

```js
if (role === "ADMIN") {
  // ❌ THIS IS NOT SECURITY
}
```

### ❌ Do NOT store sensitive JWT data in Redux

```js
state.token = jwt; // ❌
```

### ❌ Do NOT hide buttons and assume security

UI hiding ≠ authorization

***

# ✅ Security Separation (VERY IMPORTANT)

| Layer   | Responsibility                        |
| ------- | ------------------------------------- |
| Backend | Real security (JWT validation, roles) |
| JWT     | Trusted claims                        |
| Redux   | UI behavior only                      |
| React   | Rendering & navigation                |

***

# ✅ Token Refresh Case

When access token expires:

1.  Backend issues new JWT
2.  Decode roles again
3.  Update Redux

```js
dispatch(loginSuccess({
  user: decodedUser,
  roles: decoded.roles
}));
```

✅ Redux always reflects latest roles

***

# ✅ Interview‑Ready Answer (MEMORIZE)

> “Roles come from the JWT payload and are decoded on login. Redux stores roles only for UI‑level decisions like route guards and component rendering, while the backend enforces actual authorization on every request.”

